english:
  title: Postface to the Compendium of Agriculture and Sericulture
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "The ways of Goryeo are rough and humble, yet its people lack skill in the art of livelihood. The farming families look only to heaven, and thus when drought or flood arrives, calamity follows swift. They consume sparingly—noble and commoner, old and young alike subsist on naught but vegetables, dried fish, and preserved meat. Rice is valued highly while millet is scorned; hemp abounds but silk is scarce. So the people appear hollow within and frail without, like those risen freshly from sickness—eight or nine in ten are thus afflicted. At funerals and sacrifices they abstain from flesh, yet at feasts they slaughter oxen and horses, taking their fill of wild game. \n\nAll humans possess the organs of sense—ears, eyes, mouth, nose—and from these arise desires for sound, sight, fragrance, and taste. Warmth and softness comfort the body; richness and sweetness delight the tongue. All wish for abundance and fear want. This nature is the same among all peoples under heaven. Why then should Goryeo alone be different? \n\nTo be abundant without excess, frugal without baseness, grounded in benevolence and righteousness, and ordered by proper measure—this is the golden mean established by the sages, the very source of human virtue. Yet we show mercy to five chickens and one pig, creatures of no use, unwilling to end their lives; we readily slay oxen and horses whose great labor serves us; we boldly endure the hardships of hunting that may maim our limbs or cost us our lives; yet we hesitate to take the beasts we ourselves have reared. In thus confusing the weighty and the trivial, we corrupt righteousness and overturn order, losing our true nature. Is this then the people's failing alone? I grieve deeply for this.\n\nIt has long been my vision to regulate the people's livelihood and restore the Way of Kings, yet I have accomplished nothing. How can this be remedied?\n\nRecently, Kang Si, an official of Sham Province, wrote to me concerning the Compendium of Agriculture and Sericulture. This work was transmitted by Yi Si-jung, the Apricot Village scholar, to his nephew Yu Hwak, and thence came to Kang Si's hands. Every method for securing food and clothing, every means of accumulating wealth, every technique for cultivation and breeding—all are gathered, classified, and illuminated as if by candlelight. Truly, this is an excellent guide to livelihood. Kang Si wishes to have it engraved and distributed throughout the provinces, but fears the large characters and heavy binding will hinder its transmission to distant places. He has therefore had it transcribed in fine script, and Administrator Kim has provided silk to support the expense. He requests that I record this at the end.\n\nI have long contemplated this work and savored its wisdom. My sorrow for our customs runs deep, and I have held this office no brief time, yet I have never dared propose its implementation. This is my shame. Yet from this, one can see that Kang Si's vision aligns with my own. The regulation of livelihood and the restoration of the Way of Kings does not end here. Has Kang Si considered this deeply? If such measures are truly to be enacted, they must begin with the rejection of heterodox teachings. Otherwise, our customs will never change, and this book will remain mere words upon paper. Let Kang Si redouble his efforts."
  footnotes:
    - Yi Si-jung (李時中), known as the 'Apricot Village Scholar' (杏村), was a prominent Goryeo official and scholar from whom this important agricultural text descended.
    - The 'Way of Kings' (王道) refers to the benevolent governance through virtue emphasized in Confucian thought, as opposed to rule through force or punishment.
    - Lee Saek's regret about not implementing these reforms while in office reflects his broader frustration with Goryeo's inability to adopt Song Chinese institutional reforms.
